<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,152,879]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,339,618,644]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Etymology.</emphasis>
Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Perez-Gelabert" authorityYear="2009" box="[419,517,619,644]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incisura">
<emphasis box="[419,517,619,644]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">incisura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, for notch, referring to the long notch or emargination on the dorsoposterior margin of the epandrium.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,152,879]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,319,696,722]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Perez-Gelabert" authorityYear="2009" box="[327,514,696,721]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incisura">
<emphasis box="[327,514,696,721]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Efferia incisura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the long scutal and scutellar setae being as long or longer than the scape, and the characters of the terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[765,909,735,761]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="29.[151,269,1888,1912]" captionTargetBox="[152,1432,245,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,194,1864]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Efferia incisura sp. nov. Male terminalia, lateral view: 46. Intact, left side; 47. Gonostylus with thick sclerotization; 48. Phallus; and 49. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia, lateral view: 50. Ovipositor; 51. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455830/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs. 46–51</figureCitation>
). Additionally, the male is recognized by the mostly white setose palpi, absence of a costal dilation, and the white tomentose abdominal segments 6–7. The female is further distinguished by the long R4 recurrent vein, mostly black setose palpi, and the wide tomentose sides of tergite 7.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
